ing role in shaping modern-day Scotland and the identity of its people.Written by scholars of distinction, these chapters represent ground-breaking research in the field of Scotland’s complex and often-changing relationship with the British empire in the period. The introduction that opens the collection will be viewed for years to come as the single most important historiographical statement on Scotland and empire during the tumultuous years of the twentieth century. A final chapter from Stuart Ward and Jimmi Østergaard Nielsen covers the 2014 referendum.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aStudies in Imperialism 2017. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aBritish Columbia.  aBritish Empire.  aDavid Livingstone.  aHamilton by-election.  aMau Mau insurgency.  aScottish emigration.  aScottish military tradition.  aScottish newspapers.  aScottish referenda.  aSuez Crisis.  aanti-colonialism.  adecolonisation.  adevolutionary politics.  aethnic diaspora.  ajute industry.  atwentieth century.1 aAllan, Stuart, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlass, Bryan S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlass, Bryan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHarper, Marjory, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHowe, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacKenzie, John M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacKenzie, John M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMorton, Graeme, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNielsen, Jimmi Østergaard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStewart, Gordon T., econtributor